{"componentChunkName":"component---src-page-post-tsx","path":"/an-everyone-culture","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Markus Tacker","tagLine":"Software Crafter","description":"Software Crafter building üå©Ô∏è cloud-based cellular IoT solutions at Nordic Semiconductor.‚Äã\n\t\tMentor. Speaker. ‚ÄãConference & Community builder. Camper. üèïÔ∏è üöê","gitHubUrl":"https://github.com/coderbyheart/coderbyheart.com.git","siteUrl":"https://coderbyheart.com","twitter":"@coderbyheart","defaultCard":"https://images.ctfassets.net/bncv3c2gt878/3Jk4P6nFPNzaz1gsguktk8/350b7e4ddb2c7d86416243d9902920e2/social-card-default-2020.png"}}},"pageContext":{"page":{"id":"3bb075ea-628b-53ee-a090-da0523cd3c9b","name":"an-everyone-culture","relativeDirectory":"post","relativePath":"post/an-everyone-culture.md","remark":{"htmlAst":{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"In "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"An Everyone Culture"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.amazon.de/dp/1625278624/ref=cm_sw_r_tw_dp_x_Zrb1xbW37FWHT","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" the authors "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Robert Kegan and Lisa Laskow Lahey"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"http://mindsatwork.com/who-we-are/","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nexplore "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Deliberately Developmental Organizations"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" (DDOs)."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"In these organizations "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"adult development"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" is part of the core business model:\nthey don't invest into the personal development of their employees because they\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"must"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" but because they believe that there is a fundamental different concept of\nthe employee: they are part of the organization "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"with all their warts"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":". The idea\nis: in many organizations a lot of effort is invested into appearing to be\nperfect or flawless, to cover up ones insecurities and to cover for others\ninsecurities (\"I let you get through with "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"this"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" because you will do the same\nfor me on another occasion\"). The authors call this "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"having a second, unpaid\njob"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":". How organizations where able to eliminite this second, unpaid job by\nbringing your full self to work in order to work on your shortcomings on company\ntime is explained with a lot of real-life examples."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"You get to look inside three organizations from completely different industries:\nmovie-theaters / real estate, hedge fund managament, and IT. You get to\nexperience working in such an environment basically from a first person view and\nare taken directly into real situations. All have one astounding similarity in\ncommon: these organizations have created a safe environment to be yourself and\nbe open about your problems. They go even so far to make them publically\navailable for everyone in the organization to look up. And this is the crucial\npart: creating a nurturing and helpful environment is not easy to build, and it\nchanges the understanding of what "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"being at work"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" means so radically, that it\ndoes not fit everybody. Constantly working on yourself, personally and\nprofessionally, is nothing everybody is able to do. But the results are\nfascinating; they are only postive in this book, though."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The second important concept in the book is the removal of professional\nseniority. The idea that one can keep working in your job basically forever is\ndiscarded. Which makes perfectly sense today because of two things: no job role\nwill be there forever and not change, things you've learned two years ago are\nsoon outdated. But more important the longer you do a job the less creative and\nopen you are for new and better ideas and change. In DDOs, as soon as you master\nyour current role you are rotated to a coaching role for this position and after\nthat assigned to a new role where you start over "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"as a newbie"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":". And this is true\nfor every job in those organizations not only for those employees that want to\nwork like this anyway. This creates a constant influx of new ideas in all parts\nof the organization and enabled the three examples in the book to become\nrespected industry leaders."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"I've taken away a lot of new ideas about how organizations can be run, and\nlearned how attractive personal development in the context of your organization\ncan be and that the benefits are bigger then I would have estimated."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"This book is also a great example for the saying \"Culture eats strategy for\nbreakfast\": no strategy can deal with crisis like a team where everybody knows\neveryones shortcomings and how to work with them."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Highly recommended!"}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"}],"type":"root","data":{"quirksMode":false}},"frontmatter":{"title":"An Everyone Culture","subtitle":null,"noheadline":null,"date":"2016-09-10T16:00:00.000Z","abstract":"Book review of An Everyone Culture by Robert Kegan and Lisa Laskow Lahey\n","lang":null},"headings":[]}},"Footer":{"id":"cfe5b9e2-511c-5615-992a-dab82e1f8ed7","name":"Footer","relativeDirectory":"","relativePath":"Footer.md","remark":{"htmlAst":{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Software Crafter building üå©Ô∏è cloud-based cellular IoT solutions at\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Nordic Semiconductor"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://nordicsemi.com/","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"."},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nMentor. Speaker. Conference & Community builder. Camper. üèïÔ∏è üöê"}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[],"tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1